&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Are you open to using a foreach loop instead of array_search?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If so try this:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$haystack = array('something', 'someone', 'somewhere', 'some');
$needle = 'some';

foreach($haystack as $key=&amp;gt;$straw){
    if($straw === $needle){
        $straws[$key] = $straw;
        }
    }

print_r($straws);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;it will print &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;Array ( [3] =&amp;gt; some ) 
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Or you could use &lt;a href="http://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-keys.php" rel="nofollow noreferrer"&gt;array_keys()&lt;/a&gt; with the search value specified.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then, using the same $haystack and $needle above:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$result = array_keys($haystack,$needle,TRUE);
print_r($result);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This returns:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;Array ( [0] =&amp;gt; 3 ) 
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first argument is the array to return keys from, The second arg is the search value, if you include this arg, then only keys from array elements that match the search value are returned.  Including the third boolean arg tells the function to use match type as well (===).  &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

